Hi, I have been playing with this scenario a little more.

First, you might have noticed there is a bug when writing a rule (in typescript or js) that compares ids. I just fixed the bug and published a new build. 

Guaranteeing auto-increment ids or accurate timestamps when originating events in a distributed system is a difficult problem to solve. Trying to reason about consecutive messages comparing consecutive Ids or timestamps is not advisable. The good news is: there is a better way.

From a purely declarative (no side-effects) perspective, it is possible to write a set of rules to decide what to do with three consecutive messages. It is important to define the outcome of each combination.

```typescript
const set: any = d.ruleset('test', 
    {
        whenAll: [
            c['id0'] = m['type'].eq('error'),
            c['id1'] = m['type'].eq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])),
            c['id2'] = m['type'].eq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])).and(m['id'].neq(c['id1']['id'])),
        ],
        run: (c) => {
            console.log('TRIGGERED: 3 error events in a row');
        },
    },
    {
        whenAll: [
            c['id0'] = m['type'].neq('error'),
            c['id1'] = m['type'].eq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])),
            c['id2'] = m['type'].eq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])).and(m['id'].neq(c['id1']['id'])),
        ],
        run: (c) => {
            console.log('TRIGGERED: 1 success and 2 error events in a row');
        },
    },
    {
        whenAll: [
            c['id0'] = m['type'].neq('error'),
            c['id1'] = m['type'].neq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])),
            c['id2'] = m['type'].eq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])).and(m['id'].neq(c['id1']['id'])),
        ],
        run: (c) => {
            console.log('TRIGGERED: 2 success and 1 error event in a row');
        },
    },
    {
        whenAll: [
            c['id0'] = m['type'].neq('error'),
            c['id1'] = m['type'].neq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])),
            c['id2'] = m['type'].neq('error').and(m['id'].neq(c['id0']['id'])).and(m['id'].neq(c['id1']['id'])),
        ],
        run: (c) => {
            console.log('TRIGGERED: 3 success events in a row');
        },
    }
);
```
While the ruleset above will detect three consecutive error messages in a tumbling window, you might want to detect three consecutive error messages in a sliding window. 

Being practical, it is possible to use the ruleset state (or context):

```typescript
const set: any = d.ruleset('test', 
    {
        whenAll: [
            s['errors'].gte(3),
        ],
        run: (c) => {
            console.log('3 consecutive errors detected');
            c['s']['errors'] = 0;       
        },
    },
    {
        whenAll: [
            m['type'].ex(),
        ],
        run: (c) => {
            if (c['m']['type'] == 'error') {
                c['s']['errors'] = isNaN(c['s']['errors']) ? 0: c['s']['errors'] + 1;
            } else {
                c['s']['errors'] = 0;
            }
        },
    }
);
```
The ruleset above will detect three consecutive errors in a sliding window. There is a performance penalty: an action is triggered for every event, while in the first example an action is triggered for every 3 events.

