@NikolajBjorner @wintersteiger 
Okay I've taken a look over the ``clause_allocator`` code and have some questions/comments.

First **why** is there this special cased (``#ifdef _AMD64_``) code in the ``clause_allocator``? If I've read the code correctly then it seems give you a way to refer to a ``clause`` using a 32-bit integer rather than a 64-bit pointer. Why is this desirable? It can't be to save memory or for performance because your implementation makes both of those worse: you allocate more memory (``size`` may be larger in ``clause_allocator::mk_clause()``) and in order to actually get a pointer to a ``clause`` you have to pointer arithmetic and then dereference.

Second how is ``clause_allocator::get_segment()`` supposed to work? I found a bug in the bounds check there (see #453). Once I fixed that then those checks were failing in the AddressSanitizer build. It seems that ``clause_allocator`` tries to create too many segments. Looking at the code it looks like it has a flawed assumption in it. Here it is (with my fix)

```c++
    unsigned clause_allocator::get_segment(size_t ptr) {
        SASSERT((ptr & c_aligment_mask) == 0);
        ptr &= ~0xFFFFFFFFull; // Keep only high part
        unsigned i = 0;
        for (i = 0; i < m_num_segments; ++i)
            if (m_segments[i] == ptr)
                return i;
        i = m_num_segments;
        m_num_segments++;
        SASSERT(m_num_segments <= c_max_segments);
        if (i >= c_max_segments)
            throw default_exception("segment out of range");
        m_segments[i] = ptr;
        return i;
    }
```

It looks like the code seems to assume that upper most 32-bits of the passed in ``ptr`` value can be used as a unique key for each segment. The code checks if it has seen the masked ``ptr`` before and if not it adds another segment. The number of segments is bounded by ``c_max_segments`` which is currently 8 ( ``1 << 3``), if it runs out of segments an ``SASSERT`` will now fire (#453 adds this check). It looks like ``ptr`` is actually a pointer address (see ``clause_allocator::get_offset()``). The flawed assumption here is that a ``clause_allocator`` will only ever see values of ``ptr`` where the 32 most significant bits have at most 8 different values. This assumption clearly breaks when doing an AddressSanitized build because we run out of segments (ASan changes the memory layout so the pointer addresses you get back may be different to a not sanitized build). You **cannot** make this assumption because you have no control over the addresses that the underlying malloc implementation gives you. The fact that this issue has not been hit before means you have been relying on the behaviours of the different malloc implementations that Z3 has been tested on.

It is up to you how you think fix this issue but it seems to me it would be best to remove the specialised ``clause_allocator`` code of x86_64 because its design is broken.

